C++ emArray.h: dynamic array template with copy-on-write and stable iterators.

69 files outside emCore use this type.

Rust equivalent: Vec<T>

Method mapping (verified — identical functionality, different names):
  GetCount        -> len()
  SetCount        -> resize() / truncate()
  Compact         -> shrink_to_fit()
  Get/operator[]  -> index operator / .get()
  Set             -> index assignment
  Add             -> push() / extend()
  Insert          -> insert()
  Remove          -> remove()
  Clear           -> clear()
  IsEmpty         -> is_empty()
  Sort            -> sort_by()
  BinarySearch    -> binary_search_by()
  GetSubArray     -> slice [a..b] / .to_vec()
  Extract         -> drain(range).collect()
  Replace         -> splice()
  emSortArray     -> slice::sort_by()
  emBinarySearch  -> slice::binary_search_by()

Composable from stdlib (no direct equivalent, but trivially built):
  BinaryInsert / BinaryInsertIfNew / BinaryInsertOrReplace /
  BinaryReplace / BinaryRemove / BinaryRemoveByKey
    -> binary_search_by() + insert() / remove()
  NOT VERIFIED: whether any of the 69 outside-emCore files call these methods.

No Rust equivalent exists for:
  GetWritable / MakeNonShared — COW mutation triggers. Vec has single owner;
    &mut Vec guarantees exclusive access at compile time.
  GetDataRefCount — COW refcount. Vec never shares backing data.
  TuningLevel — controls COW copy thresholds and preallocation strategy.
  PointerToIndex — converts raw pointer into backing buffer to array index.
  emArray::Iterator — persistent cursor that survives array mutations and
    COW clones. Rust iterators borrow the collection immutably.

Semantic differences (unverified impact on app code):
  COW copy: C++ "emArray b = a" shares data (O(1)), mutation of either
    triggers deep copy. Rust "let b = a.clone()" always deep copies.
    NOT VERIFIED: whether any of the 69 outside-emCore files rely on
    cheap copy semantics or on the original remaining valid after copy.

  Stable iterators: C++ emArray::Iterator auto-adjusts when elements are
    removed or when COW clone occurs. Rust prevents mutation during iteration.
    NOT VERIFIED: whether any code mutates an emArray while iterating.

  Persistent cursor: C++ emArray::Iterator can be stored as a struct field
    and remain valid across method calls. Rust iterators are typically scoped.
    NOT VERIFIED: whether any code stores an emArray::Iterator as a field.
